Write a function that can find an element in an array using the passed callback (predicate) function. Something that works like the JavaScript [Array.prototype.find()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/find) method. The main difference is that the function can also find nested elements.

The function takes four arguments: 
  - an array of elements with the same structure;
  - a callback (predicate) function (one argument â€“ an array item);
  - a key of the nested array (optional, `children` by default);
  - a default value that returns if nothing was found (optional, `null` by default).

The function returns the found item. If there is more than one, the closest to the first element (first children, then the next by index).

```javascript
const data = [
  { id: 1, children: [{ id: 11 }, { id: 12 }] },
  { id: 2 },
  { id: 3, children: [{ id: 31 }, { id: 32, children: [{ id: 321 }] }] },
]

findRecursive(data, element => element.id === 32, 'children', null);
// returns { id: 32, children: [{ id: 321 }] }
```
